.com/story/tech/gaming/2018/10/26/red-dead-redemption-2-rockstar-games-western-classic/1650295002/ |title='Red Dead Redemption 2': First impressions from once upon a time in the West |first=Mike |last=Snider |date=October 26, 2018 |website=[[USA Today]] |access-date=April 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407011534/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2018/10/26/red-dead-redemption-2-rockstar-games-western-classic/1650295002/ |archive-date=April 7, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VentureBeat: CCO\">{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2012/02/20/xgirl-virtual-girlfriend-for-xbox/ |title=Red Dead Redemption studio worked on an \"interactive girlfriend project\" for Microsoft |first=Sebastian |last=Haley |date=February 20, 2012 |website=[[VentureBeat]] |access-date=December 10, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210154630/https://venturebeat.com/2012/02/20/xgirl-virtual-girlfriend-for-xbox/ |archive-date=December 10, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VG247: Agent listed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vg247.com/2013/05/16/agent-pops-up-again-on-rockstar-resume-alongside-gta-5/ |title=Agent listed as \"currently in development\" on Rockstar resume |first=Stephany |last=Nunneley |date=May 16, 2013 |website=[[VG247]] |access-date=October 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107031227/https://www.vg247.com/2013/05/16/agent-pops-up-again-on-rockstar-resume-alongside-gta-5/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VG247: Another E3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vg247.com/2014/05/24/agent-trademark-renewed/ |title=Another E3, another possibility for an Agent reveal |first=Stephany |last=Nunneley |date=May 24, 2014 |website=[[VG247]] |access-date=October 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107033304/https://www.vg247.com/2014/05/24/agent-trademark-renewed/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VG247: new open-world game\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vg247.com/2012/02/06/rockstar-san-diego-hiring-for-new-open-world-game/ |title=Rockstar San Diego hiring for new open-world game |first=Debabrata |last=Nath |date=February 6, 2012 |website=[[VG247]] |access-date=October 30, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107032143/https://www.vg247.com/2012/02/06/rockstar-san-diego-hiring-for-new-open-world-game/ |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VideoGamer.com: new open-world game\">{{cite web |url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/rockstar-san-diego-hiring-for-new-open-world-game-working-on-next-gen-engine |title=Rockstar San Diego hiring for new open-world game, working on next-gen engine? |first=Neon |last=Kelly |date=February 7, 2012 |website=VideoGamer.com |access-date=October 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107024548/https://www.videogamer.com/news/rockstar-san-diego-hiring-for-new-open-world-game-working-on-next-gen-engine |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"VideoGamer.com: Take-Two CEO\">{{cite web |url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/take-two-ceo-hints-at-red-dead-redemption-2 |title=Take-Two CEO hints at Red Dead Redemption 2 |first=David |last=Scammell |date=July 31, 2013 |website=VideoGamer.com |access-date=November 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042556/https://www.videogamer.com/news/take-two-ceo-hints-at-red-dead-redemption-2 |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Wired: Dollar a Minute\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.wired.com/1994/05/realies/ |title=Dollar a Minute |first=Michael |last=Krantz |date=May 1, 1994 |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |access-date=November 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042310/https://www.wired.com/1994/05/realies/ |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"XVG: Sky Pirates VR\">{{cite web |url=http://xtreme-video-games.tripod.com/news/030100/pirates.htm |title=Sky Pirates VR |first=Michael |last=Puccini |date=February 29, 2000 |website=Xtreme Video Games |access-date=September 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010725100815/http://xtreme-video-games.tripod.com/news/030100/pirates.htm |archive-date=July 25, 2001 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Rockstar Games}}\n{{Take-Two Interactive}}\n\n[[Category:1984 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Carlsbad, California]]\n[[Category:Rockstar Games|*]]\n[[Category:Take-Two Interactive divisions and subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Video game companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n", "name_user": "IceWelder", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRockstar Games deals and acquisition (2000\u20132006)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rockstar_San_Diego"}
{"title_page": "Willis D. Crittenberger", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Willis D. Crittenberger\n|image= Willis D. Crittenberger.JPG\n|image_size= 190px\n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \"Critt\"\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1890|12|02}}\n|birth_place= [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1980|08|04|1890|12|02}}\n|death_place= [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1913\u20131952\n|rank= [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[First United States Army]]<br/>[[United States Southern Command|Caribbean Command]]<br/>[[United States Southern Command|Caribbean Defense Command]]<br/>[[IV Corps (United States)|IV Corps]]<br/>[[XIX Corps (United States)|XIX Corps]]<br/>[[XIX Corps (United States)|III Armored Corps]]<br/>[[2nd Armored Division (United States)|2nd Armored Division]]<br/>[[2nd Armored Brigade (United States)|2nd Armored Brigade]]\n|battles= [[World War I]]<br/>[[World War II]]\n|awards= {{nowrap|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)}}<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Legion of Honour|Officer of the Legion of Honor]] (France)<br/>[[Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] (France)<br/>[[Order of Abdon Calder\u00f3n]] (Ecuador)<br/>[[Orden de Merito Militar]] (Peru)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]] '''Willis Dale Crittenberger''' (December 2, 1890 \u2013 August 4, 1980) was a senior officer of the [[United States Army]]. He was a career soldier who served with distinction during the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaign]] of [[World War II]].\n\n==Early life and military career==\nCrittenberger was born in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] on December 2, 1890. After growing up in [[Anderson, Indiana]], he was appointed to the [[United States Military Academy]] (USMA) at [[West Point, New York]] in 1909, graduating four years later on June 12, 1913 with the West Point class of 1913, two years ahead of fellow cadet, friend and infantry officer, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]].<ref>{{Citation| date=August 7, 1980| title=Obituary: General Willis D. Crittenberger; A Leader of Allied Forces in Italy| periodical=New York Times| location=New York| pages=B11| url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FA0817FF3A5F12728DDDAE0894D0405B8084F1D3| accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> Crittenberger was then [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[United States Cavalry|Cavalry Branch]] of the [[United States Army]] and his first posting was with the [[3rd Cavalry Regiment (United States)|3rd Cavalry Regiment]], then stationed at [[Fort Hood]], [[Texas]].<ref>{{Citation| date=December 29, 1952| title=People (Crittenberger retirement)| periodical=Time| location=New York| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,822573-2,00.html | accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> Among his many classmates were [[Geoffrey Keyes]], [[Henry Balding Lewis]], [[Paul Newgarden]], [[Richard U. Nicholas]], [[Charles H. Corlett]], [[William A. McCullogh]], [[Douglass T. Greene]], [[Robert M. Perkins]], [[Louis A. Craig]], [[Carlos Brewer]], [[William R. Schmidt]], [[Alexander Patch]], [[Robert L. Spragins]], [[Francis K. Newcomer]], [[Henry B. Cheadle]], [[Lunsford E. Oliver]] and [[William L. Roberts (United States Army officer)|William L. Roberts]]. Like Crittenberger, they were all destined to become [[general officer]]s.\n\n==Between the wars==\nUnable to see service overseas in [[World War I]], where he remained in the United States training recruits, Crittenberger's advanced military education included the [[United States Army Cavalry School]] at [[Fort Riley]], [[Kansas]] in 1924, the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]] at [[Fort Leavenworth]], Kansas in 1925 and the [[United States Army War College]] at [[Washington Barracks]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1930. After assignments to [[Fort Knox]], [[Kentucky]], the [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment (Mechanized)]]'s new home in 1934, he served on [[Staff (military)|staff]] positions to the Chief of Cavalry in [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and, towards the end of the [[interwar period]], realizing that the cavalry's role in any future conflict would be limited (as World War I and [[trench warfare]] had proved), becoming increasingly interested in [[Armoured warfare|armored warfare]], and became [[chief of staff]] for the [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]].\n\n==World War II==\nWith the onset of the United States entry into [[World War II]], Crittenberger, with the rank of [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], was commanding the [[2nd Armored Brigade (United States)|2nd Armored Brigade]] of the [[2nd Armored Division (United States)|2nd Armored Division]], under Major General [[George S. Patton]]. In February 1942, two months after the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941 and the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[German declaration of war against the United States (1941)|declaration of war on the United States]] four days later, Crittenberger assumed command of the division while Patton was sent to command the [[I Armored Corps (United States)|I Armored Corps]]. In August 1942, relinquishing command of the 2nd Armored Division to Major General [[Ernest N. Harmon]], Crittenberger, now a major general, organized, trained and commanded the [[XIX Corps (United States)|III Armored Corps]], composed of the [[7th Armored Division (United States)|7th]] and [[11th Armored Division (United States)|11th Armored Division]]s at [[Fort Polk|Camp Polk]], [[Louisiana]]. Redesignated as [[XIX Corps (United States)|XIX Corps]] in October 1943, Crittenberger brought XIX Corps to England in January 1944.\n\n[[File:Willis Crittenberger and George Marshall 1942.jpg|thumb|left|On the left, Major General Willis Crittenberger and, on the right, the [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] General [[George Marshall]] at [[Fort Benning]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], 1942.]]\n\nIn early 1944, General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], the [[Supreme Allied Commander]] for the impending [[Invasion of Normandy|Normandy invasion]], initially selected Crittenberger as one of three corps commanders, along with Major General [[Leonard T. Gerow]], commanding [[V Corps (United States)|V Corps]], and Major General [[Roscoe B. Woodruff]], commanding [[VII Corps (United States)|VII Corps]], for the invasion. All three were well-known and trusted by General Eisenhower. However, Lieutenant General [[Omar Bradley]], who Eisenhower selected as the [[First United States Army]] commander for the [[Normandy landings|D-Day invasion]], replaced Eisenhower's picks, seeking differing temperaments and commanders that had more combat experience. At the same time, Lieutenant General [[Jacob L. Devers]], Commanding General (CG) of the [[Mediterranean Theater of Operations|North African Theater of Operations, United States Army]] (NATOUSA), was seeking a corps commander for the [[United States Army North|Fifth United States Army]]'s [[IV Corps (United States)|IV Corps]] for the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaign]] and Crittenberger was chosen.<ref>{{Citation| last =D'Este| first =Carlo=| publication-date =2002| year =2002| title =Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life| location =New York| publisher =Henry Holt| isbn =978-0-8050-5686-0| url =https://books.google.com/?id=sLZI7Gm_KXIC&pg=PA486&lpg=PA486&dq=willis+d+crittenberger| accessdate =2007-10-03}}</ref>\n\nCrittenberger relinquished command of XIX Corps, briefly, to Major General Woodruff, who soon handed over to Major General [[Charles H. Corlett]], a classmate from the West Point class of 1913, and departed England for the [[Mediterranean Theater of Operations]], assuming command of IV Corps from Major General [[Alexander Patch]], another West Point classmate, in Italy on March 20, 1944. Held in reserve during the early stages of the Italian Campaign, IV Corps replaced the [[VI Corps (United States)|VI Corps]], under Major General [[Lucian Truscott]], in the front line after the liberation of the Italian capital of [[Rome]] in early June. Crittenberger's corps, coming under command of Lieutenant General [[Mark W. Clark]]'s Fifth United States Army (itself part of the [[Allied Armies in Italy]], later designated [[15th Army Group]], commanded by British General [[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|Sir Harold Alexander]]) later fought on through the [[Gothic Line]], in some of the toughest and most difficult fighting of the Italian Campaign.\n\nHaving the [[Brazilian Expeditionary Force|1st Brazilian Infantry]] and the [[6th Armoured Division (South Africa)|6th South African Armoured]] Divisions in its ranks, in addition to the United States [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored]], the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd Infantry]] and the [[10th Mountain]] Divisions, Crittenberger's IV Corps were in combat for over 390 days, 326 of them engaged in continuous combat. Crittenberger commanded IV Corps, still part of the Fifth Army, now commanded by Lieutenant General Lucian Truscott (like Crittenberger, a cavalryman who Crittenberger had taught while he was an instructor at the United States Army Cavalry School), after Lieutenant General Clark was promoted to the command of 15th Army Group, as the western arm of the [[Spring 1945 offensive in Italy|Allied thrust through northern Italy]] (codenamed Operation Grapeshot) to the [[Po (river)|Po River]], capturing large numbers of [[Wehrmacht|German troops]], which ended with the surrender of the remaining German forces in Italy on May 2, 1945.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Citation | date=August 7, 1980 | periodical=New York Times}}</ref> The [[end of World War II in Europe]] came soon after, followed by the [[surrender of Japan]] on September 2, 1945, almost exactly six years since the war had begun. During the campaign in Italy Crittenberger operated alongside Major General [[Geoffrey Keyes]], another of Crittenberger's West Point classmates, who was commanding [[II Corps (United States)|II Corps]].\n\n==Postwar career==\nIn the postwar years Crittenberger commanded the Caribbean Defense Command, including the [[Panama Canal Zone]], then in 1947, became first commander-in-chief of United States Caribbean Command, a regional unified theater command and predecessor to today's [[United States Southern Command]]. After a two-year stint as Commanding General of the [[First United States Army]], at [[Fort Jay]], [[Governors Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], Crittenberger concluded his active duty military career in December 1952, leaving [[New York City]] with a ticker tape parade up Broadway.<ref>{{Citation| date=December 29, 1952| title=People (Crittenberger retirement)| periodical=Time}}</ref>\n\n==Civilian career==\nIn retirement, Crittenberger advised President Dwight D. Eisenhower on national security matters. Crittenberger served as president of the United States Military Academy Association of Graduates from 1955 to 1958 and president of the Greater New York Fund.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nCrittenberger was Chairman of the Free Europe Committee for three years, from 1956 to 1959.<ref>Johanna Granville, [https://www.scribd.com/doc/13866301/RFE-and-the-Hungarian-Revolt-of-1956-by-Johanna-Granville \"Caught With Jam on Our Fingers\u201d: Radio Free Europe and the Hungarian Revolution in 1956,\u201d] ''Diplomatic History'', vol. 29, no. 5 (2005): pp. 811\u2013839.</ref><ref>{{Citation | last=Granville | first=Johanna | title=The First Domino: International Decision Making During the Hungarian Crisis of 1956 | publisher=[[Texas A & M University Press]], College Station, Texas | year=2004 | isbn=1-58544-298-4 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nCrittenberger married Josephine Frost Woodhull (1894\u20131978) on June 23, 1918. Two of his three sons served in the [[United States Armed Forces]] and died in combat. Corporal Townsend Woodhull Crittenberger (born May 13, 1925) was killed in action during the [[Rhine|Rhine River]] crossing on March 25, 1945 during the final days of World War II, aged just 19.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Colonel Dale Jackson Crittenberger (USMA 1950) (born May 27, 1927) commanding the 3rd Brigade of the [[9th Infantry Division (United States)|9th Infantry Division]] during the [[Vietnam War]] was killed in a mid-air collision on September 17, 1969 while directing combat operations, aged 42. Dale served as a White House military aide to President Eisenhower in 1959 and as a newly commissioned major received his new badge of rank from his father's old friend, the President.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nA third son, Willis D. Crittenberger, Jr. (USMA 1942) also served in the United States Army in World War II with the [[10th Armored Division (United States)|10th Armored Division]], rising from lieutenant to lieutenant colonel during the war, retiring as a major general. He later was a spokesman for the Daughters of the American Revolution.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nLieutenant General Willis Dale Crittenberger died in Chevy Chase, Maryland on August 4, 1980 at the age of 89. He was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Virginia]] with his wife and sons, Townsend and Dale.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==Decorations==\n\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] with [[Oak leaf cluster|Oak Leaf Cluster]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|ribbon=Bronze Star Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Bronze Star Medal]] with two Oak Leaf Clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Mexican Border Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Mexican Border Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=service-star|ribbon=European-African-Middle Eastern Campaign ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[European\u2013African\u2013Middle Eastern Campaign Medal]] with four Service Stars\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War II Victory Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Honour|Officer of the Legion of Honor]] (France)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Croix de guerre 1939-1945 with palm (France) - ribbon bar.png|width=60}}\n|[[Croix de Guerre]] (France)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Order of Abd\u00f3n Calder\u00f3n 1st Class (Ecuador) - ribbon bar.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of Abdon Calder\u00f3n]] (Ecuador)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=noribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Orden de Merito Militar]] (Peru)\n|}\n\n==Books==\n\n* ''The final campaign across Italy''; 1952 \u2013 His memoirs as commander of US Army IV Corps {{ISBN|85-7011-219-X}}\n* ''Some thoughts on civil defense''; 1954 4pgs Essay\n* ''Debrief report''; 1967 Dept. of the Army \u2013 Headquarters, II Field Force Vietnam Artillery 21pgs report\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{Citation\n | last=\n | first=\n | author-link=\n | publication-date=August 18, 1980\n | date=August 18, 1980\n | title=Milestones (obituary)\n | periodical=Time\n | series=\n | location=New York\n | place=\n | publisher=\n | volume=\n | issue=\n | pages=\n | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,948950,00.html\n | issn=\n | doi=\n | oclc=\n | accessdate=2008-03-09\n}}.\n\n{{Citation\n | last=\n | first=\n | author-link=\n | date=September 14, 1942 \n | title=Bigger: Indications of the U.S. Army's growing size and strength [Establishment of 3rd Armored Corps]\n | periodical=Time\n | series=\n | location=New York\n | place=\n | publisher=Time\n | volume=\n | issue=\n | pages=\n | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,802446,00.html\n | issn=\n | doi=\n | oclc=\n | accessdate=2008-03-09\n}}.\n\n{{Citation\n | last =D'Este\n | first =Carlo\n | author-link =\n | author2-link =\n | publication-date =2002\n | year =2002\n | title =Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life\n | edition =\n | volume =\n | series =\n | location =New York\n | place =\n | publisher =Henry Holt\n | id =\n | isbn =978-0-8050-5686-0\n | doi =\n | oclc =\n | url =https://books.google.com/?id=sLZI7Gm_KXIC&pg=PA486&lpg=PA486&dq=willis+d+crittenberger\n | accessdate =2007-10-03\n}}.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Willis D. Crittenberger}}\n*[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/wdcritte.htm Arlington National Cemetery page for Lt. Gen. Willis D. Crittenberger]\n*[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.net/djcritte.htm Arlington National Cemetery page for Col. Dale J. Crittenberger]\n*[http://www.xixcorps.nl/ XIX Corps Website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[George S. Patton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[2nd Armored Division (United States)|Commanding General 2nd Armored Division]]|years=February 1942 \u2013 July 1942}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ernest N. Harmon]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|command}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[XIX Corps (United States)|Commanding General III Armored Corps]]|years=1942\u20131944}}\n{{s-non|reason=Post redesignated XIX Corps}}\n|-\n{{s-new|command}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[XIX Corps (United States)|Commanding General XIX Corps]]|years=1942\u20131944}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Roscoe B. Woodruff]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alexander Patch]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[IV Corps (United States)|Commanding General IV Corps]]|years=1944\u20131945}}\n{{s-non|reason=Post deactivated}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Roscoe B. Woodruff]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[First United States Army|Commanding General First Army]]|years=1950\u20131952}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Withers A. Burress]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crittenberger Willis D.}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n[[Category:United States Army Command and General Staff College alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= Willis D. Crittenberger\n|image= Willis D. Crittenberger.JPG\n|image_size= 190px\n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \"Critt\"\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1890|12|02}}\n|birth_place= [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1980|08|04|1890|12|02}}\n|death_place= [[Chevy Chase, Maryland]]\n|placeofburial= [[Arlington National Cemetery]]\n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1913\u20131952\n|rank= [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[First United States Army]]<br/>[[United States Southern Command|Caribbean Command]]<br/>[[United States Southern Command|Caribbean Defense Command]]<br/>[[IV Corps (United States)|IV Corps]]<br/>[[XIX Corps (United States)|XIX Corps]]<br/>[[XIX Corps (United States)|III Armored Corps]]<br/>[[2nd Armored Division (United States)|2nd Armored Division]]<br/>[[2nd Armored Brigade (United States)|2nd Armored Brigade]]\n|battles= [[World War I]]<br/>[[World War II]]\n|awards= {{nowrap|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)}}<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Legion of Honour|Officer of the Legion of Honor]] (France)<br/>[[Croix de Guerre 1939\u20131945 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] (France)<br/>[[Order of Abdon Calder\u00f3n]] (Ecuador)<br/>[[Orden de Merito Militar]] (Peru)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]] '''Willis Dale Crittenberger''' (December 2, 1890 \u2013 August 4, 1980) was a senior officer of the [[United States Army]]. He was a career soldier who served with distinction during the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaign]] of [[World War II]].\n\n==Early life and military career==\nCrittenberger was born in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]] on December 2, 1890. After growing up in [[Anderson, Indiana]], he was appointed to the [[United States Military Academy]] (USMA) at [[West Point, New York]] in 1909, graduating four years later on June 12, 1913 with the West Point class of 1913, two years ahead of fellow cadet, friend and infantry officer, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]].<ref>{{Citation| date=August 7, 1980| title=Obituary: General Willis D. Crittenberger; A Leader of Allied Forces in Italy| periodical=New York Times| location=New York| pages=B11| url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FA0817FF3A5F12728DDDAE0894D0405B8084F1D3| accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> Crittenberger was then [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned]] as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[United States Cavalry|Cavalry Branch]] of the [[United States Army]] and his first posting was with the [[3rd Cavalry Regiment (United States)|3rd Cavalry Regiment]], then stationed at [[Fort Hood]], [[Texas]].<ref>{{Citation| date=December 29, 1952| title=People (Crittenberger retirement)| periodical=Time| location=New York| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,822573-2,00.html | accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> Among his many classmates were [[Geoffrey Keyes]], [[Henry Balding Lewis]], [[Paul Newgarden]], [[Richard U. Nicholas]], [[Charles H. Corlett]], [[William A. McCullogh]], [[Douglass T. Greene]], [[Robert M. Perkins]], [[Louis A. Craig]], [[Carlos Brewer]], [[William R. Schmidt]], [[Alexander Patch]], [[Robert L. Spragins]], [[Francis K. Newcomer]], [[Henry B. Cheadle]], [[Lunsford E. Oliver]] and [[William L. Roberts (United States Army officer)|William L. Roberts]]. Like Crittenberger, they were all destined to become [[general officer]]s.\n\n==Between the wars==\nUnable to see service overseas in [[World War I]], where he remained in the United States training recruits, Crittenberger's advanced military education included the [[United States Army Cavalry School]] at [[Fort Riley]], [[Kansas]] in 1924, the [[United States Army Command and General Staff College]] at [[Fort Leavenworth]], Kansas in 1925 and the [[United States Army War College]] at [[Washington Barracks]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1930. After assignments to [[Fort Knox]], [[Kentucky]], the [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment (Mechanized)]]'s new home in 1934, he served on [[Staff (military)|staff]] positions to the Chief of Cavalry in [[Washington (state)|Washington]] and, towards the end of the [[interwar period]], realizing that the cavalry's role in any future conflict would be limited (as World War I and [[trench warfare]] had proved), becoming increasingly interested in [[Armoured warfare|armored warfare]], and became [[chief of staff]] for the [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored Division]].\n\n==World War II==\nWith the onset of the United States entry into [[World War II]], Crittenberger, with the rank of [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]], was commanding the [[2nd Armored Brigade (United States)|2nd Armored Brigade]] of the [[2nd Armored Division (United States)|2nd Armored Division]], under Major General [[George S. Patton]]. In February 1942, two months after the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[attack on Pearl Harbor]] on December 7, 1941 and the [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[German declaration of war against the United States (1941)|declaration of war on the United States]] four days later, Crittenberger assumed command of the division while Patton was sent to command the [[I Armored Corps (United States)|I Armored Corps]]. In August 1942, relinquishing command of the 2nd Armored Division to Major General [[Ernest N. Harmon]], Crittenberger, now a major general, organized, trained and commanded the [[XIX Corps (United States)|III Armored Corps]], composed of the [[7th Armored Division (United States)|7th]] and [[11th Armored Division (United States)|11th Armored Division]]s at [[Fort Polk|Camp Polk]], [[Louisiana]]. Redesignated as [[XIX Corps (United States)|XIX Corps]] in October 1943, Crittenberger brought XIX Corps to England in January 1944.\n\n[[File:Willis Crittenberger and George Marshall 1942.jpg|thumb|left|On the left, Major General Willis Crittenberger and, on the right, the [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] General [[George Marshall]] at [[Fort Benning]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], 1942.]]\n\nIn early 1944, General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], the [[Supreme Allied Commander]] for the impending [[Invasion of Normandy|Normandy invasion]], initially selected Crittenberger as one of three corps commanders, along with Major General [[Leonard T. Gerow]], commanding [[V Corps (United States)|V Corps]], and Major General [[Roscoe B. Woodruff]], commanding [[VII Corps (United States)|VII Corps]], for the invasion. All three were well-known and trusted by General Eisenhower. However, Lieutenant General [[Omar Bradley]], who Eisenhower selected as the [[First United States Army]] commander for the [[Normandy landings|D-Day invasion]], replaced Eisenhower's picks, seeking differing temperaments and commanders that had more combat experience. At the same time, Lieutenant General [[Jacob L. Devers]], Commanding General (CG) of the [[Mediterranean Theater of Operations|North African Theater of Operations, United States Army]] (NATOUSA), was seeking a corps commander for the [[United States Army North|Fifth United States Army]]'s [[IV Corps (United States)|IV Corps]] for the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaign]] and Crittenberger was chosen.<ref>{{Citation| last =D'Este| first =Carlo=| publication-date =2002| year =2002| title =Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life| location =New York| publisher =Henry Holt| isbn =978-0-8050-5686-0| url =https://books.google.com/?id=sLZI7Gm_KXIC&pg=PA486&lpg=PA486&dq=willis+d+crittenberger| accessdate =2007-10-03}}</ref>\n\nCrittenberger relinquished command of XIX Corps, briefly, to Major General Woodruff, who soon handed over to Major General [[Charles H. Corlett]], a classmate from the West Point class of 1913, and departed England for the [[Mediterranean Theater of Operations]], assuming command of IV Corps from Major General [[Alexander Patch]], another West Point classmate, in Italy on March 20, 1944. Held in reserve during the early stages of the Italian Campaign, IV Corps replaced the [[VI Corps (United States)|VI Corps]], under Major General [[Lucian Truscott]], in the front line after the liberation of the Italian capital of [[Rome]] in early June. Crittenberger's corps, coming under command of Lieutenant General [[Mark W. Clark]]'s Fifth United States Army (itself part of the [[Allied Armies in Italy]], later designated [[15th Army Group]], commanded by British General [[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|Sir Harold Alexander]]) later fought on through the [[Gothic Line]], in some of the toughest and most difficult fighting of the Italian Campaign.\n\nHaving the [[Brazilian Expeditionary Force|1st Brazilian Infantry]] and the [[6th Armoured Division (South Africa)|6th South African Armoured]] Divisions in its ranks, in addition to the United States [[1st Armored Division (United States)|1st Armored]], the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd Infantry]] and the [[10th Mountain]] Divisions, Crittenberger's IV Corps were in combat for over 390 days, 326 of them engaged in continuous combat. Crittenberger commanded IV Corps, still part of the Fifth Army, now commanded by Lieutenant General Lucian Truscott (like Crittenberger, a cavalryman who Crittenberger had taught while he was an instructor at the United States Army Cavalry School), after Lieutenant General Clark was promoted to the command of 15th Army Group, as the western arm of the [[Spring 1945 offensive in Italy|Allied thrust through northern Italy]] (codenamed Operation Grapeshot) to the [[Po (river)|Po River]], capturing large numbers of [[Wehrmacht|German troops]], which ended with the surrender of the remaining German forces in Italy on May 2, 1945.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Citation | date=August 7, 1980 | periodical=New York Times}}</ref> The [[end of World War II in Europe]] came soon after, followed by the [[surrender of Japan]] on September 2, 1945, almost exactly six years since the war had begun. During the campaign in Italy Crittenberger operated alongside Major General [[Geoffrey Keyes]], another of Crittenberger's West Point classmates, who was commanding [[II Corps (United States)|II Corps]].\n\n==Postwar career==\nIn the postwar years Crittenberger commanded the Caribbean Defense Command, including the [[Panama Canal Zone]], then in 1947, became first commander-in-chief of United States Caribbean Command, a regional unified theater command and predecessor to today's [[United States Southern Command]]. After a two-year stint as Commanding General of the [[First United States Army]], at [[Fort Jay]], [[Governors Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], Crittenberger concluded his active duty military career in December 1952, leaving [[New York City]] with a ticker tape parade up Broadway.<ref>{{Citation| date=December 29, 1952| title=People (Crittenberger retirement)| periodical=Time}}</ref>\n\n==Civilian career==\nIn retirement, Crittenberger advised President Dwight D. Eisenhower on national security matters. Crittenberger served as president of the United States Military Academy Association of Graduates from 1955 to 1958 and president of the Greater New York Fund.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nCrittenberger was Chairman of the Free Europe Committee for three years, from 1956 to 1959.<ref>Johanna Granville, [https://www.scribd.com/doc/13866301/RFE-and-the-Hungarian-Revolt-of-1956-by-Johanna-Granville \"Caught With Jam on Our Fingers\u201d: Radio Free Europe and the Hungarian Revolution in 1956,\u201d] ''Diplomatic History'', vol. 29, no. 5 (2005): pp. 811\u2013839.</ref><ref>{{Citation | last=Granville | first=Johanna | title=The First Domino: International Decision Making During the Hungarian Crisis of 1956 | publisher=[[Texas A & M University Press]], College Station, Texas | year=2004 | isbn=1-58544-298-4 }}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nCrittenberger married Josephine Frost Woodhull (1894\u20131978) on June 23, 1918. Two of his three sons served in the [[United States Armed Forces]] and died in combat. Corporal Townsend Woodhull Crittenberger (born May 13, 1925) was killed in action during the [[Rhine|Rhine River]] crossing on March 25, 1945 during the final days of World War II, aged just 19.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Colonel Dale Jackson Crittenberger (USMA 1950) (born May 27, 1927) commanding the 3rd Brigade of the [[9th Infantry Division (United States)|9th Infantry Division]] during the [[Vietnam War]] was killed in a mid-air collision on September 17, 1969 while directing combat operations, aged 42. Dale served as a White House military aide to President Eisenhower in 1959 and as a newly commissioned major received his new badge of rank from his father's old friend, the President.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nA third son, Willis D. Crittenberger, Jr. (USMA 1942) also served in the United States Army in World War II with the [[10th Armored Division (United States)|10th Armored Division]], rising from lieutenant to lieutenant colonel during the war, retiring as a major general. He later was a spokesman for the Daughters of the American Revolution.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nLieutenant General Willis Dale Crittenberger died in Chevy Chase, Maryland on August 4, 1980 at the age of 89. He was buried at [[Arlington National Cemetery]], [[Virginia]] with his wife and sons, Townsend and Dale.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==Decorations==\n\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] with [[Oak leaf cluster|Oak Leaf Cluster]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=oak|ribbon=Bronze Star Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Bronze Star Medal]] with two Oak Leaf Clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Mexican Border Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Mexican Border Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=World War I Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War I Victory Medal (United States)|World War I Victory Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=American Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=American Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[American Campaign Medal]]\n|-\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=4|type=service-star|ribbon=European-African-Middle Eastern Campaign ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[European\u2013African\u2013Middle Eastern Campaign Medal]] with four Service Stars\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=World War II Victory Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[World War II Victory Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[National Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion Honneur Officier ribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Legion of Honour|Officer of the Legion of Honor]] (France)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Croix de guerre 1939-1945 with palm (France) - ribbon bar.png|width=60}}\n|[[Croix de Guerre]] (France)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Order of Abd\u00f3n Calder\u00f3n 1st Class (Ecuador) - ribbon bar.png|width=60}}\n|[[Order of Abdon Calder\u00f3n]] (Ecuador)\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=noribbon.svg|width=60}}\n|[[Orden de Merito Militar]] (Peru)\n|}\n\n==Books==\n\n* ''The final campaign across Italy''; 1952 \u2013 His memoirs as commander of US Army IV Corps {{ISBN|85-7011-219-X}}\n* ''Some thoughts on civil defense''; 1954 4pgs Essay\n* ''Debrief report''; 1967 Dept. of the Army \u2013 Headquarters, II Field Force Vietnam Artillery 21pgs report\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{Citation\n | last=\n | first=\n | author-link=\n | publication-date=August 18, 1980\n | date=August 18, 1980\n | title=Milestones (obituary)\n | periodical=Time\n | series=\n | location=New York\n | place=\n | publisher=\n | volume=\n | issue=\n | pages=\n | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,948950,00.html\n | issn=\n | doi=\n | oclc=\n | accessdate=2008-03-09\n}}.\n\n{{Citation\n | last=\n | first=\n | author-link=\n | date=September 14, 1942 \n | title=Bigger: Indications of the U.S. Army's growing size and strength [Establishment of 3rd Armored Corps]\n | periodical=Time\n | series=\n | location=New York\n | place=\n | publisher=Time\n | volume=\n | issue=\n | pages=\n | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,802446,00.html\n | issn=\n | doi=\n | oclc=\n | accessdate=2008-03-09\n}}.\n\n{{Citation\n | last =D'Este\n | first =Carlo\n | author-link =\n | author2-link =\n | publication-date =2002\n | year =2002\n | title =Eisenh